ce:section.ce:para:
There are many methods to prepare CQDs, such as surface passivation by functionalization, hydrothermal carbonization of organic substances, and electro-oxidation of graphite [1,3]. Hydrothermal method could convert various precursors into CQDs. The properties of CQDs depend on the species of precursors and reaction conditions [1,3]. In this study, red emissive CQDs were fully characterized to confirm the successful preparation. Small nanodots were observed under TEM with diameters of about 5 nm (Fig. 1
                        a). At high resolution, the lattice of graphite could be recognized, suggesting that CQDs were mainly constructed by graphite (inset of Fig. 1a). The graphite structure of CQDs was confirmed by the XRD signal at 27.5° (Fig. 1b). After laser quenching, the Raman signal of CQDs could be obtained and the graphite signal was evidenced at 1582 cm−1 (G-band of sp2 carbon) in Fig. 1c. The functional groups of CQDs were reflected by IR spectrum (Fig. 1d). In the infrared spectrum, the broad band at around 3410 cm−1 was assigned to −OH/−COOH groups. The strong band at 1665 cm−1 was attributed to the CC skeletal stretching vibrations (sp2 carbon). The peak at 1283 cm−1 was assigned to CO bonds. The chemical components of CQDs were 63.37 at% of C, 11.06 at% of O and 25.57 at% of N according XPS analysis. The fluorescence of CQDs was recorded to confirm the successful synthesis (Fig. 2
                        ). The most efficient excitation was achieved at 566 nm with the strongest emission at 615 nm. By shifting the excitation wavelength, the emission wavelength shifted and the intensity changed. This suggested that there were different fluorophores in CQDs, which was the most distinct characteristics of CQDs [1,2].

The unaffected enzymatic activities implied that CQDs would not impact the decomposition activity of P. chrysosporium. Reactive brilliant red X-3B is a classical indicator for the decomposition activity of white rot fungi. The decoloration kinetics of reactive brilliant red X-3B were nearly identical for the control and the CQDs exposed groups, suggesting that CQDs did not change the decomposition activity of P. chrysosporium (Fig. 7
                        ). The degradation of sawdust was not affected by CQDs, either. The weight losses of sawdust during the three months’ degradation were about 25 % for all groups (Fig. 8
                        a). The lignin contents were nearly the same for all groups, too (Fig. 8b). These results collectively indicated that CQDs would not affect the degradation of wood after entering the environment.
